1. Introduction

In recent years, with the growth of digital media, the amount of news content being generated every day has increased dramatically. As a result, there is a growing need for methods to quickly and accurately analyze this vast amount of information. Text mining can help extract insights and trends from news articles, and is widely used in areas such as sentiment analysis, topic modeling, and information retrieval. Especially when it comes to news articles, there is significant need to understand how they work and how to interact with those, therefore in this article, we will explore the various techniques used in text mining field, to analyze existing topics and sentiments present in 6877 articles grouped into 14 categories published on Huffpost website. We will examine the top topics across articles, determine if the sentiments vary between categories and how topics are similar to the body of articles.

The dataset contains 6877 unique articles within 14 categories including Arts & Culture, Business, Comedy, Crime, Education, Entertainment, Environment, Media, Politics, Religion, Science, Sports, Tech and Women. The articles spreads almost equally across categories and after initial analysis, we have removed common stopwords, in order to understand the most used words within our articles.

Mentioned lexicon contains almost 7000 words, that could be classified as positive or negative. For each article in the dataset, we have calculated the difference between number of positive and negative words and then took the average for every category. The obvious outlier in this comparison is Crime category, which has definitely lack of positive words. The distribution vary between articles categories - for Arts & Culture, Entertainment or Media, the range is rather huge, but that can be explained with the fact, that those may contain reviews of shows or plays, which could be both positive and negative. Definitely the most consistent category is comedy, having extremely wide distribution around 0, suggesting, that most of the articles are neither positive nor negative.

3. Modeling

In the modeling part, we will evaluate the LDA method to identify common topics of articles. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is a generative probabilistic model used for topic modeling in text analysis. It assumes that each document in a corpus is generated from a mixture of latent topics and each topic is characterized by a distribution over words. The method uses Bayesian inference to estimate the topic and word distributions in a corpus, and it can be used to identify the underlying topics in a collection of documents. The results of LDA can be generally used for tasks such as document clustering, topic classification, and information retrieval. What is more, we will also analyze how the Sentiments spread across categories and if they differ between article Title and Body. In order to achieve that, we will assign sentiments to each of the words in title and body, then calculate percentage of words of each sentiment in relation to number of all words used in title/article. After that, for every row we calculate the Euclidean distance between the vector of sentiments for title and for body and take the average of that distance for every category and compare those scores.

This might suggest, that those two categories contain misleading titles, providing not clear context of what the actual articles consist of. Let’s see the basic outcome from the LDA algorithm below:

Since LDA works like PCA but for text analysis we can model all the topics within text documents by reduce the ‘dimensionality’ of the topics. It is done by decomposition of the corpus document word matrix (the larger matrix) into two parts (smaller matrices): the Document Topic Matrix and the Topic Word.

This visualization lets us understand the three topics that were extracted from the dataset. The most common words in topic 1 include “people”, “women”, “time”, and “trump”, which suggests it may represent either sociological or political news. Those most common in topic 2 include “people”, “sexual”, “women”, “school”, and “police”, suggesting that this topic represents political news. One important observation about the words in each topic is that some words, such as “women” and “people”, are common within both topics. Third topic contains, again, “people”, but also “students”, “percent”, “u.s.” and, school”.

As stated in article from tidytextmining.com “This is an advantage of topic modeling as opposed to “hard clustering” methods: topics used in natural language could have some overlap in terms of words.”

## Selecting by tf_idf

Term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) tells us quantitative how rare is the term. Accordingly to the Medium.com article: The score increases the more frequently a term occurs. However, it decreases the more often the term appears across multiple documents. We can also think of TF-IDF in this way: “How strange is it that this token is in this document?”

In our case, where we have 10 different topics in our news dataset, therefore with the use of tf-idf, we will check how rare “globally” are certain topics in our dataset, and on the other hand how there are important “locally” for given topic.

We would like to review on a few chosen categories form used dataset: Business, Science, and Environment

When it comes to Business category, we can see, that “kalanick” is at the top of our results, however, it is “uber” and “uber’s” which cumulatively outbalances “kalanick”.

Regarding to Science, interesting thing is that the SpaceX appears in final comparison while it is a private company.

Going to Environment, which top 4 is most diverse - I do not really understand the “oo” when it comes to environmental issues, however, both following words “keystone” and “emissions” seems quite meaningful.

5. Summary

In this project, we did analyze the News from Huffpost platform in terms of sentiment and mentioned topics.The biggest issue we were struggling with, was the data cleansing, but we have overcome that with adding custom stopwords as we wanted to do.

We did examine the hypothesis of if the sentiment vary between title and the article itself, coming to the conclusion, that sentiment is different for those, especially for Religion and Crime news. We have conducted the LDA method to find common topics and used TF-IDF matrix to understand commonly used terms.
